Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide
chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, sprinkle over the
@roasted white sesame seeds{5%grams}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{},
then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

Meanwhile, remove the @slow cooked beef{280%grams} from the packaging. Place in
an #ovenproof dish{} along with the juices, drizzle over the
@red Thai style paste{50%grams} and cover loosely with #foil{}.

Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Ensure it's piping hot throughout.

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, combine the @mayonnaise{32%grams} and
@sriracha sauce{15%grams} (add less if you'd prefer things milder).

Add the @coleslaw mix{120%grams} and stir together. Season with salt and pepper,
then set your slaw aside.

In another #large bowl{}, mix together the @rice vinegar{15%milliliter},
@sugar{1%tsp} and @olive oil{1%tbsp} for the dressing (see pantry for both
amounts). Season with salt and pepper.

A few mins before everything's ready, pop the @plain taco tortillas{4} (2 per person)
into the oven to warm through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the beef is cooked, remove from the oven, then discard the foil and cooking
juices. Use two #forks{} to shred the beef as finely as you can.

Stir the @sweet chilli sauce{64%grams} into the pulled beef.

Add the @baby leaf mix{50%grams} to the bowl of dressing and toss to dress.

> TIP: Don't add the leaves too early or they'll go soggy.

When everything's ready, share the tortillas between your serving plates.

Top with the spiced pulled beef, then some of the sriracha mayo slaw - as much as
you'd like.

Serve your tacos with the sesame chips and baby leaf salad alongside.

> TIP: Tacos are best eaten by hand - get stuck in!